<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="Thm_TwoLinearEqsGeometricalSoln"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle2.5/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Simultaneous solutions of two linear equations</caption>
   <associate type="Explanation">
      <unit.ref unitId="Illust_ScalarMultiplicationOfVectors"/>
      <info>
         <info.caption>Explanation: How do I test if two vectors are parallel?</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>
               <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{n}_1</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{n}_2</latex>
               </math> are parallel if there is <math>
                  <latex>t\in \RNr</latex>
               </math> with <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{n}_1=t\cdot \Vect{n}_2</latex>
               </math>. â€“ Review an illustration of this.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>Given two linear equations in <math>
               <latex>n</latex>
            </math> variables</para.body>
      </para>
      <math.display>
         <latex>
				
						\begin{array}{rcrccccrcl}
\colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{1}$}{\color{red}x_1} &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{2}$}{\color{red}x_2} &amp; + &amp; \cdots &amp; \cdots &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_{n}$}{\color{red}x_n} &amp; = &amp; {\color{blue} c} \\
\colorbox{lightgreen}{$b_{1}$}{\color{red}x_1} &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$b_{2}$}{\color{red}x_2} &amp; + &amp; \cdots &amp; \cdots &amp; + &amp; \colorbox{lightgreen}{$b_{n}$}{\color{red}x_n} &amp; = &amp; {\color{blue} d}
						\end{array}
					
			</latex>
      </math.display>
      <para>
         <para.body>form the coefficient vectors <math>
               <latex>\Vect{n}_1</latex>
            </math>, <math>
               <latex>\Vect{n}_2</latex>
            </math>, and the augmented coefficient vectors <math>
               <latex>\Vect{N}_1</latex>
            </math> given by
			</para.body>
         <index.glossary>
            <term>coefficient</term>
            <term>vector</term>
            <term>in a linear equation</term>
         </index.glossary>
         <index.glossary>
            <term>coefficient</term>
            <term>vector</term>
            <term>augmented</term>
         </index.glossary>
         <index.glossary>
            <term>augmented</term>
            <term>coefficient vector</term>
         </index.glossary>
      </para>
      <table align="center" border="1" cellpadding="2">
         <row>
            <cell>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\colorbox{lightgreen}{$\Vect{n}_1 := (a_1,\dots ,a_n)$}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </cell>
            <cell>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\colorbox{lightgreen}{$\Vect{n}_2 := (b_1,\dots ,b_n)$}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </cell>
         </row>
         <row>
            <cell>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{N}_1 := (\colorbox{lightgreen}{$a_1,\dots ,a_n$},{\color{blue} c})</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </cell>
            <cell>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{N}_2 := (\colorbox{lightgreen}{$b_1,\dots ,b_n$},{\color{blue} d})</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </cell>
         </row>
      </table>
      <para>
         <para.body>If <math>
               <latex>\Vect{n}_1,\Vect{n}_2\neq \Vect{0}</latex>
            </math> the following hold:</para.body>
      </para>
      <ul>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>If <math>
                     <latex>n=2</latex>
                  </math>, and if <math>
                     <latex>\colorbox{lightgreen}{$\Vect{n}_1$}</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\colorbox{lightgreen}{$\Vect{n}_2$}</latex>
                  </math> are not parallel, then the given equations have exactly  one common solution.</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>If <math>
                     <latex>n\geq 3</latex>
                  </math>, and if <math>
                     <latex>\colorbox{lightgreen}{$\Vect{n}_1$}</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\colorbox{lightgreen}{$\Vect{n}_2$}</latex>
                  </math> are not parallel, then the given equations have infinitely many common solutions.</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>If <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{n}_1</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{n}_2</latex>
                  </math> are parallel but <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{N}_1</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\mathbf{N}_2</latex>
                  </math> are not parallel, the given equations have no simultaneous solutions.</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>If <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{N}_1</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{N}_2</latex>
                  </math> are parallel, one of the equations is redundant, and the solutions hyperplane of one equation also forms the simultaneous solution set of both equations.</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
      </ul>
   </statement.theorem>
</theorem>
